,{"from":{"fname":"history.india.emergency","id":"wlxFd7HbmqxwksWlen6Wp","vaultName":"vault"},"type":"backlink","position":{"start":{"line":6,"column":80,"offset":414},"end":{"line":6,"column":125,"offset":459},"indent":[]},"value":"history.india.indira_gandhi"},{"from":{"fname":"history.india.indo_pak_war_1971","id":"Fpm81lfFrZwYvjkpiBj5m","vaultName":"vault"},"type":"backlink","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1,"offset":875},"end":{"line":17,"column":48,"offset":922},"indent":[]},"value":"history.india.indira_gandhi"},{"from":{"fname":"history.india.nationalization_of_banks","id":"tkx1eYaDXd4GkTduTFO6I","vaultName":"vault"},"type":"backlink","position":{"start":{"line":2,"column":10,"offset":10},"end":{"line":2,"column":57,"offset":57},"indent":[]},"value":"history.india.indira_gandhi"}],"anchors":{"nationalization-of-banks-1969":{"type":"header","text":"Nationalization of banks, 1969","value":"nationalization-of-banks-1969","line":12,"column":0,"depth":2},"congress-split":{"type":"header","text":"Congress split","value":"congress-split","line":17,"column":0,"depth":2},"indo-pakistani-war-1971":{"type":"header","text":"Indo Pakistani war, 1971","value":"indo-pakistani-war-1971","line":27,"column":0,"depth":2},"emergency-1975":{"type":"header","text":"Emergency, 1975","value":"emergency-1975","line":31,"column":0,"depth":2}},"children":[],"parent":"x6V2SrfdyeC4Vo1AJ643s","data":{}},"body":"<h1 id=\"indira-gandhi\">Indira Gandhi<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#indira-gandhi\"></a></h1>\n<p>Indira Gandhi became Prime Minister on <a href=\"/notes/U5sfDC1JM84fCmi20tid4\">Lal Bahadur Shastri's</a> death.\nMorarji Desai was initially finance minister and deputy prime minister under Indira Gandhi.</p>\n<h2 id=\"nationalization-of-banks-1969\">Nationalization of banks, 1969<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#nationalization-of-banks-1969\"></a></h2>\n<p>She was responsible for the <a href=\"/notes/tkx1eYaDXd4GkTduTFO6I\">nationalization of banks</a>, fired Desai\nas finance minister because he opposed the nationalization.</p>\n<h2 id=\"congress-split\">Congress split<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#congress-split\"></a></h2>\n<p>The election of a new President led to a split in the Congress when Mrs Gandhi did not support the official\nCongress candidate and instead supported an independent. Eventually, she was expelled from the Congress for\n\"indiscipline\".</p>\n<p>Congress was split into two: Congress(O) and Congress(R). (old and reform) / (organization and requisitionist).</p>\n<p>Eventually, Congress (R) won the general elections in 1971 with a huge majority (352 of 518 seats).</p>\n<h2 id=\"indo-pakistani-war-1971\">Indo Pakistani war, 1971<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#indo-pakistani-war-1971\"></a></h2>\n<p>Indira was PM during the <a href=\"/notes/Fpm81lfFrZwYvjkpiBj5m\">war</a> in 1971, a major figure in the creation of Bangladesh.</p>\n<h2 id=\"emergency-1975\">Emergency, 1975<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#emergency-1975\"></a></h2>\n<p>Indira is most well-known for declaring an <a href=\"/notes/wlxFd7HbmqxwksWlen6Wp\">emergency</a>,\ndue to \"internal disturbances\". This was followed by more authoritarian practises like\nputting dissenters in jail, press censorship, and extreme implementation of policies like\nforced sterilization.</p>\n<p>The emergency was eventually lifted 19 months later in 1977.</p>\n<hr>\n<strong>Backlinks</strong>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"/\">Notes</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/notes/wlxFd7HbmqxwksWlen6Wp\">Emergency, 1975</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/notes/Fpm81lfFrZwYvjkpiBj5m\">India Pakistan war, 1971</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/notes/tkx1eYaDXd4GkTduTFO6I\">Nationalization of Banks, 1969</a></li>\n</ul>","noteIndex":{"id":"root","title":"Notes","desc":"","updated":1676546314176,"created":1595961348801,"custom":{"nav_order":0,"permali